<center>'''[''' An empty head towards’ till dawn. ''']'''</center>



<center><div style="text-align: justify; max-width: 750px;"><br>{{Class Custom Image|bg-image=Silent Horizon.jpeg|class=Habitable|safety=Safe|security=Secure|entity=Stable|hexagon=⏳︎|text-color=white}}



<br/>The shoreline stretched toward the horizon until it vanished beyond the edge of sight. Broken slabs of concrete lay drowned beneath moss, while the coast itself carried an artificial charm that repelled the notion of any true beach; a manufactured resort facade stripped of warmth. Jagged rocks enclosed the pavement from end to end, breaking the advance of the waves before they could ever reach the shore.

<br>Fragments of life, carried ashore by the tides, endured within the cracks between mankind’s decorations, though they were not the only things left behind there. Benches lined the coastal promenade as if placed for an absent crowd, accompanied by streetlamps, Mediterranean shrubs, and carefully arranged flora. Damp wooden seats and scattered waste bins stood untouched beneath the open sky, yet across the endless horizon, there remained neither litter nor any trace of humanity.

<br>The livelihood of the entire land once depended upon this union. The waves delivered the ocean’s blessings to those who dwelled upon the coast. Long ago, mankind wielded all manner of tools, drawing treasures from the sea to forge their own vision of paradise. The shoreline had once been a fishing town.

<br>Sunset was said to follow a path of its own. The townsfolk spoke of it so often that legends began to emerge; from blue into rose, from rose into violet, the sky would drift endlessly through color, and thus the town was never believed to truly sleep. In pride, they named it '''The Land Where the Sun Never Sets'''. From the distant islands, they waved toward the horizon with hope, crossing oceans in vessels of their own making, abandoning their former lives in pursuit of something greater.

</div>



</center><center><br><br><br><div style="display: inline-block; background:rgba (0, 0, 0, 0.8); border: 4px double white;">
[[File:Silent Horizon-2.jpeg|600px|center|link=]]
</div><br><br><br/></center>

<center>'''[''' Aside from all the pasts’ wherefore now. ''']'''</center>



<center><div style="text-align: justify; max-width: 750px;"><br/>Remnants of the old coastal paradises could still be found scattered along the shore. Before abandoning these lands, mankind had left behind vast quantities of resources within their concrete fortresses, having built their comfort between the endless sea and the unknown beyond. These single-story lodgings remained furnished with stable electricity, luxurious interiors, and enough resting space to satisfy any weary traveler.


<br>Yet the inland regions beyond the coast had long since become sealed away. Humanity, in pursuit of its own comfort, raised walls against nature itself and withdrew behind them, isolating their kingdoms from the world beyond the shore. It was often said that those who ventured inland from these self-contained societies were never heard from again.


<br>And so the tide had turned; the civilization once believed unreachable would soon be witnessed for the final time.

</div>



<div class="titleblock"><span class="titlebox">Addendum - Silent Horizon</span>

<br/><center><big><div style="font-size:45px;">''' 𖤓 '''</div></big></center><br>

<center><br><br><br><div style="display: inline-block; background:rgba (0, 0, 0, 0.8); border: 4px double white;">
[[File:Silent Horizon-3.jpeg|600px|center|link=]]
</div><br><br><br/></center>

<center>'''[''' All quiet on the Silent Horizon. ''']'''</center>


<center><br/>''Beyond power and glory, our kingdom sought possession of a far holier virtue: peace.''</center>


<div style="text-align: justify; max-width: 600px;"><br>Humanity has always hungered for change. To grow, to learn, to love, to claim purpose for oneself. Within a single lifetime, how many things do we not attempt to become? A profession, a devotion, perhaps even something as fleeting as a quiet morning ritual. Yet beneath all transient desires, something dormant remains within us; a longing that judges every pause in our lives as emptiness, forever seeking meaning beyond temporary comforts.


<br>Throughout existence, mankind has always searched for summits. A mountain peak, the surface of the moon, horizons untouched by those before us. We fear stagnation as though it were death itself, yet we fear collapse even more; every misstep threatens to cast us into ruin. Stability becomes sacred to us, even as we curse the stillness it brings.</div>


<center><br/>''And so we build shells around ourselves.''</center>


<div style="text-align: justify; max-width: 600px;"><br>To perceive, to interpret, to learn from suffering—these are the gifts that crown a man king within the confines of his own mind. We reinforce those fragile walls endlessly, fearing that if they were ever broken, the kingdom within would perish alongside them.


<br>Humanity became a structure that no longer opened itself to the world; it turned its back outward, gazing only toward distant horizons while retreating deeper into its own comfort. Hidden within that shell, the seeds of despair had already taken root.


Through all this, we searched for answers within the '''Silent Horizon'''. Yet perhaps the answer was never beyond the horizon at all. Perhaps these lands were simply meant to open their gates once more.<br/></div>

<br/><br/><center><big><div style="font-size:45px;">''' 𖤓 '''</div></big></center><br/>
</div>


<div style="text-align: justify; max-width: 750px;"><br>Rumors surrounding the '''Silent Horizon''' had long since begun to spread beyond the coastline itself. Certain claimed that the shore greeted each visitor differently, as though the land possessed a memory of its own. In time, many came to refer to the region as '''ye' merely land'''; others called it the '''Silent Horizon'''.


<br>Though no gates to these lands had ever been formally discovered, stories continued to speak of tickets offered in the names of unseen guests. Entire fortunes were lost in pursuit of them. Some believed that those who [[Level 92|''lost themselves'']] eventually found their way here regardless, as though the coastline answered questions no other land could bear to ask. Those who arrived upon its shores were seldom said to return. Such expressions persisted among ye’ circles, spoken: “Those who drift beyond the horizon have merely departed for distant lands.”</div>

<center><br><br><br><div style="display: inline-block; background:rgba (0, 0, 0, 0.8); border: 4px double white;">
[[File:Silent Horizon-4.jpeg|600px|center|link=]]
</div><br><br><br/></center>

<br><center>'''[''' Time flies on ye’ the coasting land. ''']'''</center>


<div style="text-align: justify; max-width: 500px;"><br>Hourglasses were also said to appear throughout the region in unnatural abundance. Public opinion remained divided; some regarded them as omens of misfortune, while others insisted they served as passages leading beyond the shoreline itself. Yet among the older tales, another interpretation endured. Sands within them measure memory. And thus, neither the inhabitants nor the visitors were ever truly seen again.</div>



